Title: Queen of Katwe - Official Trailer
Comment:
This is one of the best and most beautiful movies I have ever watched. It littery dropped me to tears.

Now to reply to those comments below. I have been in Uganda 5 times. Amazing place, an amazing culture, its a place you will always wanna visit over and over again. I adapted to their way of living, learnt one of their language Kiganda which they very much use in the movie. They speak English everywhere especially the youth and I mean everywhere even in the villages. It is so full of life. Happiness comes from within, they truly know how to keep it at its best. That place is just full of life, worth visiting especially if you wanna cleanse your soul.

For those tourist maniacs, You will get way way way way way more than you need. Plus weekends don't exist there. The party life is so incomparable to anywhere in the world and I have been to lots of places. So party till you die, just make sure you pick you grave before hitting the maniac button.

Title: Queen of Katwe - Official Trailer
Comment:
My summary of the movie (ENTIRE MOVIE, CONTAINS SPOILERS)
Phiona lives poorly with her mother, and her younger brother Richard. Her mom's enemy, Night, who is also Phiona's sister, hangs out with a man named Theo, who is seen as a bad character. Phiona walks and stumbles upon a playgroup that specializes in chess. When the teacher, Robert, notices her standing outside, he invites her. She kept coming, where she even got fed. Phiona was treated badly by the other kids by how bad she smelled,  but hung around to learn not to play chess. She soon discovered that she was slowly devoting her life to chess. She began to play more games and beat the #1 player in the playgroup. She continues to play, and beats everyone she plays with. She gets entered into contests with older kids, until she was to be found at a worldwide serious match of chess. Phiona tries hard to beat the enemy and ends up losing. She then starts to regret everything. She runs outside in the snow and cries. Robert comes outside and comforts her. "I acted too soon, you were not ready." He said. When they arrived back home, she starts to get more practice. When she gathers her courage, she goes to another contest, with a full grown adult from Russia, who she managed to somehow beat. Everyone cheered. Back at home, the next day a gloomy storm ran over Uganda. Harriet (Phiona's mom) had unknowingly asked Night to watch over Richsrd while she ran a few errands. The storm flooded the streets about 3 feet up. Richard remained on a hammock, screaming for help. Harriet runs in to save a Richard. When she meets Night, Night confesses she was out with Theo. Then Phiona came along. Harriet and Night fought for good 5 minutes until Night exclaimed "I'm pregnant.". The next days after, every house was destroyed, causing Phiona and her family to live on the streets again. As for Phiona, she never gave up. She kept winning against others, and every time she won, she got some sort of money. That brought Harriet to buy a house for the family. Then, after that happened, Phiona became greedy, she got her hair done every time she got an award and she was too lazy to do anything. Robert confronted her. "You must get up" he commanded. Phiona listened. She did not like her greedy self either, but she had fallen into that hole. She began to quickly change. Night had her baby, and after doing loads of praying to the gods, her and Harriet became friendly. Everyone became friends.

I'm proudly African (Nigerian) , and I have to say they're doing a great job. I won't lie, I sometimes find it insulting that every time someone does an African movie they tend to portray us as totally poverty stricken animals and leave out the beautiful parts of Africa. But I'm not going to be too blind to see what this movie was aimed at achieving and how there are actually a lot of stories like this (starting from the slums into success) in Africa. 
The The creator is Ugandan, the girl actor is Ugandan, the director has lived in Uganda for 27 years and it's a true story about a Ugandan girl; that's as original and real as it gets.

Title: Queen of Katwe - Official Trailer
Comment: HOPE, POWER, COURAGE defined. I've been to the harsh Katwe slum in Kampala. And I've met the courageous chess (and soccer) coach who has mentored Phiona. To overcome the kinds of odds Phiona has overcome is beyond astonishing. The book by Tim Crothers should be on everyone's reading list. Simply to jar us into understanding that we are all more powerful than we think we are. It looks like the movie might rise to the true occasion of what Phiona is still doing to this day. That hope is alive & brilliant especially in the darkest and most ruthless of circumstances.
